Dear all,

I have come accross a certain kind of operators, and I wonder if they
have a name or have been encountered before.

We work internally in a topos with a subobject classifier =CE=A9. For the
purposes of this discussion, call a monotone map  f : =CE=A9 =E2=86=92 =CE=
=A9 *good* if

(*)       =E2=88=80 p : =CE=A9, f (f p =E2=87=92 p)

is valid in the topos.

Some examples of good maps are:

1. The identity map.
2. The double negation map.
3. For any q =E2=88=88 =CE=A9, the j-operator p =E2=86=A6 (q =E2=87=92 p).

Is the condition (*) known? Can you think of other examples of good
maps (perhaps in specific toposes)?

I have so far just one connection: in provability logic condition (*)
appears (without the universal quantifier) as the antecedent of L=C3=B6b's
theorem, which sttates that =E2=96=A1 (=E2=96=A1 p =E2=87=92 p) =E2=87=92 =
=E2=96=A1 p.

With kind regards,

Andrej


